<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Codesigning entitlements for the three FFS binaries (ffs, ffs-daemon,
  ffs-mcp) on macOS. Applied by scripts/codesign-macos.sh and by the
  CI release workflow per task_33 + ADR-023.

  Why these specific entitlements:

  * keychain-access-groups — partitions Keychain Services entries so
    all three FFS binaries share one logical bucket. Without this,
    macOS partitions entries by code-signing identity AND by launch
    context (interactive vs. launchd), and the daemon (launched by
    launchd) reads an empty keychain even when the CLI (launched
    interactively) wrote an entry seconds earlier. The shared
    access group makes those writes mutually visible.

  * com.apple.security.app-sandbox = false — FFS reads + writes
    ~/.ffs/ outside any Apple-defined sandbox container. The
    keychain-access-groups entitlement requires being explicit
    about sandbox state; setting `false` here just states the
    obvious so codesign doesn't refuse the entitlement.

  Team ID 3S9R9K2L38 is the project lead's Apple Developer Team ID.
  The access group is namespaced under it (`<team>.<group>`) per
  Apple's app-group naming convention.
-->
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>keychain-access-groups</key>
    <array>
        <string>3S9R9K2L38.com.ffs.shared</string>
    </array>
    <key>com.apple.security.app-sandbox</key>
    <false/>
</dict>
</plist>
